T1  - Optimal accommodation by strong policymakers under incomplete information
AU  - Cukierman, Alex
AU  - Liviatan, Nissan
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 27
IS  - 1
SP  - 99
EP  - 127
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/02/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(91)90006-A
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030439329190006A
AB  - This paper examines the optimal behavior of a policymaker who is able to precommit (labelled ‘strong’) when the public entertains the possibility that he is either strong or weak (unable to precommit). The main result is that, in the presence of doubts about their type, it is optimal, even for strong policymakers, to partially accommodate inflationary expectations. This contrasts with Vickers (1986) who finds that when strength is conceived in terms of the relative concern for employment the strong policymaker inflates less under incomplete than under full information. The paper also provides a theory of endogenous announcements.
